<br>
Apparently, Photoshop sucks when it comes to drawing hair. Painter handles the tablet strokes better (Photoshop tends to handle it too slow, thus, you get polygonal strokes). Then again, maybe it's because i don't have a G4 800Mhz desktop system ;o; <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chocoking>ChocoKing</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(5/12/03 9:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm35.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://chiyoko.homestead.com/files/yattasml.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Slower, but better</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I was just thinking that it might actually be better to use a wacom tablet and draw the hair strand by strand, using Painter (use the scratchboard tool). It takes more time though, but it's worth it. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
